You're very welcome! I'm happy to help you create this tool. This will be a robust, self-contained HTML file that handles the CSV parsing complexities you mentioned and presents the data in a clearly styled table.

Here's the single HTML file:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>CSV to Table Parser</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            color: #333;
        }

        h1 {
            color: #0056b3;
            text-align: center;
            margin-bottom: 30px;
        }

        .container {
            max-width: 1000px;
            margin: 0 auto;
            background-color: #fff;
            padding: 25px;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }

        label {
            display: block;
            margin-bottom: 8px;
            font-weight: bold;
            color: #555;
        }

        textarea {
            width: 100%;
            height: 200px;
            padding: 12px;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-sizing: border-box; /* Include padding in width/height */
            font-size: 1em;
            resize: vertical;
            font-family: monospace; /* Good for data entry */
        }

        button {
            display: block;
            width: 200px;
            padding: 12px 20px;
            margin: 0 auto 30px auto;
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            font-size: 1.1em;
            cursor: pointer;
            transition: background-color 0.3s ease, transform 0.2s ease;
        }

        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
            transform: translateY(-2px);
        }

        button:active {
            transform: translateY(0);
        }

        #outputTableContainer {
            margin-top: 30px;
            border-top: 1px solid #eee;
            padding-top: 20px;
        }

        #outputTableContainer h2 {
            color: #0056b3;
            margin-bottom: 15px;
            text-align: center;
        }

        .table-responsive {
            overflow-x: auto; /* Ensures table is scrollable on small screens */
            border: 1px solid #ddd; /* Outer border for the table area */
            border-radius: 5px;
        }

        table {
            width: 100%;
            border-collapse: collapse;
            min-width: 600px; /* Ensure table doesn't get too squished */
        }

        th, td {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            text-align: left;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            word-break: break-word; /* Prevent long words from overflowing */
        }

        th {
            background-color: #e9e9e9;
            font-weight: bold;
            color: #333;
            position: sticky; /* Keep header visible when scrolling horizontally */
            top: 0;
            z-index: 1; /* Ensure header is above content */
        }

        tr:nth-child(even) {
            background-color: #f9f9f9; /* Alternating row color */
        }

        tr:hover {
            background-color: #e0f2f7; /* Hover effect for rows */
        }

        .error-message {
            color: #d9534f;
            background-color: #f2dede;
            border: 1px solid #ebccd1;
            padding: 10px;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            font-weight: bold;
            text-align: center;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>CSV to HTML Table Parser</h1>

        <label for="csvInput">Paste your CSV data here:</label>
        <textarea id="csvInput" placeholder="Paste your CSV data here...
Example:
Name,Age,City
"John Doe",30,"New York"
"Jane Smith",25,"London, UK"
"Peter, Jones",40,"Paris"
"Quoted ""Value""",50,"Berlin"
"></textarea>

        <button id="parseButton">Parse CSV to Table</button>

        <div id="outputTableContainer">
            <h2>Parsed Data Table</h2>
            <div class="table-responsive">
                <table id="csvTable">
                    <thead>
                        <!-- Headers will be inserted here -->
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <!-- Data rows will be inserted here -->
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
            const csvInput = document.getElementById('csvInput');
            const parseButton = document.getElementById('parseButton');
            const csvTable = document.getElementById('csvTable');
            const tableHead = csvTable.querySelector('thead');
            const tableBody = csvTable.querySelector('tbody');
            const outputTableContainer = document.getElementById('outputTableContainer');

            // Initial state: hide the table container
            outputTableContainer.style.display = 'none';

            parseButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
                const csvText = csvInput.value.trim();
                if (!csvText) {
                    displayErrorMessage("Please paste some CSV data into the textarea.");
                    return;
                }

                try {
                    const parsedData = parseCSV(csvText);
                    renderTable(parsedData);
                    outputTableContainer.style.display = 'block'; // Show the table
                } catch (error) {
                    displayErrorMessage("Error parsing CSV: " + error.message);
                    outputTableContainer.style.display = 'none'; // Hide if error
                }
            });

            function displayErrorMessage(message) {
                // Remove existing error messages
                const existingError = document.querySelector('.error-message');
                if (existingError) {
                    existingError.remove();
                }

                const errorDiv = document.createElement('div');
                errorDiv.className = 'error-message';
                errorDiv.textContent = message;
                csvInput.parentNode.insertBefore(errorDiv, csvInput.nextSibling); // Insert after textarea
            }

            /**
             * Parses CSV text into a 2D array of strings.
             * Handles quoted fields, commas within quotes, and escaped quotes.
             * @param {string} csvString The raw CSV text.
             * @returns {string[][]} A 2D array representing the CSV data.
             */
            function parseCSV(csvString) {
                const lines = csvString.split(/\r?\n/);
                const data = [];

                lines.forEach(line => {
                    if (!line.trim()) return; // Skip empty lines

                    const row = [];
                    let inQuote = false;
                    let field = '';

                    for (let i = 0; i < line.length; i++) {
                        const char = line[i];

                        if (char === '"') {
                            if (inQuote && line[i + 1] === '"') {
                                // Escaped quote: "" becomes "
                                field += '"';
                                i++; // Skip the next quote
                            } else {
                                // Start or end of a quote
                                inQuote = !inQuote;
                            }
                        } else if (char === ',' && !inQuote) {
                            // End of a field
                            row.push(field.trim());
                            field = '';
                        } else {
                            // Regular character
                            field += char;
                        }
                    }
                    // Push the last field of the row
                    row.push(field.trim());
                    data.push(row);
                });

                return data;
            }

            /**
             * Renders the parsed CSV data into the HTML table.
             * @param {string[][]} data A 2D array of CSV data.
             */
            function renderTable(data) {
                tableHead.innerHTML = '';
                tableBody.innerHTML = '';

                if (data.length === 0) {
                    displayErrorMessage("No data found after parsing.");
                    return;
                }

                // Remove any previous error messages
                const existingError = document.querySelector('.error-message');
                if (existingError) {
                    existingError.remove();
                }

                // Determine the maximum number of columns for consistent table structure
                const maxCols = data.reduce((max, row) => Math.max(max, row.length), 0);

                // Create header row (assuming first row is header, or generate generic if not enough rows)
                const headerRow = document.createElement('tr');
                // If there's at least one row, use its content for headers.
                // Otherwise, generate generic "Column X" headers.
                const headers = data.length > 0 ? data[0] : Array.from({ length: maxCols }, (_, i) => `Column ${i + 1}`);

                // If the first row is used as headers, remove it from the data for the body
                const dataRows = data.length > 0 ? data.slice(1) : [];

                // Create header cells
                headers.forEach(headerText => {
                    const th = document.createElement('th');
                    th.textContent = headerText;
                    headerRow.appendChild(th);
                });
                tableHead.appendChild(headerRow);

                // Fill in any missing header cells if subsequent rows have more columns
                while (headerRow.children.length < maxCols) {
                    const th = document.createElement('th');
                    th.textContent = `Column ${headerRow.children.length + 1}`;
                    headerRow.appendChild(th);
                }


                // Create data rows
                dataRows.forEach(rowData => {
                    const tr = document.createElement('tr');
                    // Ensure each row has 'maxCols' cells for consistent structure
                    for (let i = 0; i < maxCols; i++) {
                        const td = document.createElement('td');
                        td.textContent = rowData[i] !== undefined ? rowData[i] : ''; // Handle varying column counts
                        tr.appendChild(td);
                    }
                    tableBody.appendChild(tr);
                });
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use:

1.  **Save:** Copy the entire code block above and paste it into a file named `index.html` (or any `.html` name).
2.  **Open:** Open the `index.html` file in your web browser.
3.  **Paste:** Paste your CSV data into the large text area.
4.  **Parse:** Click the "Parse CSV to Table" button.

### Key Features and Explanations:

1.  **Self-Contained:** Everything is in one HTML file (HTML, CSS, JavaScript).
2.  **Robust CSV Parsing (`parseCSV` function):**
    *   **Quoted Fields:** Correctly identifies fields enclosed in double quotes.
    *   **Commas within Quotes:** Acknowledges that commas inside quoted fields are part of the field, not delimiters.
    *   **Escaped Quotes:** Handles `""` inside a quoted field as a single literal `"` character.
    *   **Line Breaks:** Splits lines correctly using `/\r?\n/` to handle both Windows (`\r\n`) and Unix (`\n`) line endings.
    *   **Trimming:** Trims whitespace from fields after parsing.
3.  **Dynamic Table Generation (`renderTable` function):**
    *   Clears previous table content.
    *   **Header Row:** Uses the first row of your CSV data as table headers (`<th>`).
    *   **Varying Column Counts:**
        *   It determines the `maxCols` from all rows to ensure all table rows (`<tr>`) have the same number of cells (`<td>`).
        *   If a row has fewer columns than `maxCols`, the extra cells are left empty (`''`), maintaining a consistent table structure.
        *   If a subsequent row has *more* columns than the initial header row, it dynamically adds generic "Column X" headers to accommodate.
    *   **Empty Rows:** Skips entirely empty lines in the CSV input.
4.  **Styling (CSS):**
    *   **Clean and Modern:** Uses a clean, easy-to-read font and color scheme.
    *   **Alternating Row Colors:** `tr:nth-child(even)` provides visual separation for rows.
    *   **Clear Borders:** `border: 1px solid #ddd;` on `th` and `td` for distinct cell boundaries.
    *   **Responsive Table:** The `.table-responsive` class with `overflow-x: auto;` ensures the table is horizontally scrollable on smaller screens if it's too wide.
    *   **Sticky Header:** `position: sticky; top: 0;` on `th` keeps the table header visible when scrolling horizontally within the `.table-responsive` container.
    *   **Hover Effect:** `tr:hover` provides visual feedback when hovering over rows.
    *   **Error Messages:** Provides clear, styled error messages if parsing fails or input is empty.
5.  **User Experience (JavaScript):**
    *   **Initial State:** The output table is hidden until data is successfully parsed.
    *   **Placeholder Text:** Guides the user on what to paste.
    *   **Error Handling:** Uses a `try-catch` block to gracefully handle potential parsing errors and display user-friendly messages.

This solution should meet all your requirements effectively! Let me know if you have any further questions or need adjustments.

